cs.CY, cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.HC, cs.IR 

This paper focuses on the use of social computing systems (such as Wikipedia) to document and connect historical and contemporary events related to the Black Lives Matter movement. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the following sub-categories: 

- cs.CY (Computers and Society): This sub-category covers the social and ethical aspects of computing, including the impact of technology on society and social movements. 
- cs.SI (Social and Information Networks): This sub-category covers the analysis of social networks and their impact on information dissemination and collective action. 
- cs.SD (Software Engineering): This sub-category covers the development and maintenance of software systems, including social computing systems like Wikipedia. 
- cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction): This sub-category covers the design and evaluation of interactive systems, including social computing systems that support collaboration and knowledge sharing. 
- cs.IR (Information Retrieval): This sub-category covers the retrieval and analysis of information from large datasets, including Wikipedia articles related to the Black Lives Matter movement.
